Salt marshes are an important part of coastal systems and provide many ecological services such as habitat for wildlife and fish, removing pollutants, storing carbon, and reducing wave energy from storms.  Storm such as hurricanes can have negative or positive effects on salt marshes.  For example, hurricanes can cause major erosion and marsh loss or they can provide a much needed source of sediment.  Hurricane Sandy made landfall near Brigantine, New Jersey on October 29, 2012 with storm tides exceeding 2 m and coastal inundation of over 1 m.  Given the intensity of the storm, the prolonged period of flooding and high water levels in coastal marshes, we anticipated large impacts to nearby salt marshes.  Two years of data collection prior to Hurricane Sandy in salt marshes of both Barnegat Bay and Delaware Bay in New Jersey provided the opportunity to evaluate the impacts of the storm.  
For this study, we collected post-storm data on wetland elevation change, short-term accretion rates, plant biomass, percent organic and mineral sedimentation, soil organic matter, organic carbon, and total nitrogen with depth, and tidal creek water chemistry, including total suspended solid, nitrate-nitrite, and ammonium concentration and compared them to 2011 and 2012 pre-storm data.  This pre- and post storm analyses allowed the opportunity to observe the effect of this severe disturbance on ecological processes in salt marshes including feedbacks between elevation, mineral sedimentation, plant structure, and carbon burial.
Overall, we found very little impact of Hurricane Sandy to salt marsh platforms.  A few millimeters of erosion of surface sediment was measured in one site that had been undergoing a conversion to open water prior to the storm.  Most likely, the lack of vegetation that can stabilize sediments may have contributed to the erosion at that marsh.  A few millimeters of temporary subsurface compression was measured at a salt marsh along the Maurice River in the Delaware Bay.  The only significant changes were in the aboveground biomass at a few sites, which may be due to the flooding and flushing of porewater.  There was evidence of removal of Spartina patens litter at Reedy Creek, which likely was removed and redistributed by storm flooding.  Any change to plant biomass due to Sandy, however, is expected to be short-term, as it can be highly dependent on current year climatic conditions and sea level.  There was no evidence that the hurricane deposited sediment or wrack on the marsh platform in any of the study sites.  It is likely that much of the material carried by the flood waters of the storm passed over the marsh and were concentrated and deposited at the tree line or areas with structure taller than marsh grass.  Although, there were few effects of the storm on the marsh platform, this information is important for predicting and modeling future storm impacts and for local wetland managers to understand the role of storms in marsh dynamics.



